15 effect of dividing the attention of local boards of education, local school system
16 administrators, and public school administrators, with increasing attention paid to
17 administrative matters at the expense of decreasing attention paid to supporting and
18 improving student learning; and
19 WHEREAS, it is critical that state and local resources and efforts should be primarily
20 focused on supporting and improving student learning rather than complying with legal
21 mandates, especially such mandates that have become outmoded, are practically
22 unenforceable, or are no longer the priority of state and local governing authorities; and
23 WHEREAS, a review of existing mandates relating to public school administration is needed
24 for legislators, education leaders, and community stakeholders to examine and evaluate best
25 practices for reducing and prioritizing mandates for public school administrators, and to
26 recommend legislative and policy initiatives to that end.
27 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES:
28 (1) Creation of House study committee. There is created the House Study Committee
29 on Reducing and Prioritizing Mandates for Public School Administration.
30 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of six members of the
31 House of Representatives to be appointed by the Speaker of the House of
32 Representatives. The Speaker of the House of Representatives shall designate a member
33 of the committee as chairperson of the committee.
34 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
35 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
36 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate.
37 (4) Meetings. The chairperson shall call all meetings of the committee. The committee
38 may conduct such meetings at such places and at such times as it may deem necessary or
